      "content": "You raise a powerful point about how allowing mandatory opt-outs for core beliefs could undermine the very idea of freedom if laws are set unilaterally by the state. Many philosophers agree that religious exemption is necessary to prevent a secular state from becoming coercive, even if it creates inequality in practice. The tension lies in determining just how deep the state can go before it ceases to protect liberty, rather than simply enforcing diversity. Ultimately, preserving the right to define one's own moral life usually takes precedence over perfect legal uniformity.",
